  <h1>CBD and the Endocannabinoid System</h1>
  <img src='/logo-farm-doc.png' class='small center' />
  <section class='fd-faq' id='f1'>
    <p class='fd-faqheader'>What is the Endocannabinoid System?</p>
    <div class='fd-answer'>
      <ul>
        <li>Large, cell membrane receptor system comprised of CB1 and CB2 receptors
          <ul>
            <li>CB1 receptors predominate in the CNS, but are also widely scattered in the peripheral nervous system, and other tissues.</li>
            <li>CB2 receptors are found predominantly on muscle, adipose tissue, and immune cells, but are also scattered through the brain, mostly on glial cells.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Discovered in 1992 by Dr. Mechoulam and others.</li>
      </ul>
      <img src='/cbdguides/endocannabinoid_system.jpg' class='center medium' alt='The humany body is home to a set of receptors called the endocannabinoid sytem, pictured here showing various receptor sites in the liver, brain and elsewhere.' />
      <ul>
        <li>In general the receptor system:
          <ul>
            <li>Increases energy consumption and storage in response to physical exertion</li>
            <li>Modulates emotional responses (balances mood)</li>
            <li>Blunts inflammatory responses</li>
            <li>Modulates pain</li>
            <li>Restores homeostasis:
              <ul>
                <li>Following psychological stress by blunting the effects of inhibitory or excitatory nuerotransmitters in the nervous system</li>
                <li>Following physical exertion/exercise, by increasing energy storage</li>
                <li>Following physical injury by modulating pain and inflammatory responses</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class='fd-references print-hidden'>
        <p><strong>External References</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href='https://www.nature.com/articles/npp2017130'>Overview of Endocannabinoid System</a>, <em>Nature Journal</em> online</li>
          <li><a href='https://www.nature.com/articles/s41380-018-0215-1'>Endocannabinoid Effect on Psychological Stress</a>, <em>Nature Journal</em> online</li>
          <li><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6444701/'>Endocannabinoid Effect on Energy Expenditure</a>, <em>NCBI</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class='fd-faq' id='f2'>
    <p class='fd-faqheader'>What endogenous molecules (Endocannabinoids) activate the Endocannabinoid System?</p>
    <div class='fd-answer'>
      <ul>
        <li>The primary endocannabinoids are N-arachidonoylethanolamide (Anandamide:  AEA) and 2-arachidonoylglcyerol (2-AG).
          <ul>
            <li>Anandamide is manufactured by nerve, muscle, immune and adipose cells.  In the CNS, its actions are primarily mediated through the CB1 receptor, and peripherally primarily through the CB2 receptor.</li>
            <li>2-AG is concentrated mainly in the brain where most of its actions are mediated through the CB1 receptor.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>The endocannabinoids are unique neurotransmitters, in that:
          <ul>
            <li>they are fatty acid based</li>
            <li>they are not stored and released by vesicles, but are produced on demand by post-synaptic cells</li>
            <li>their production and release are primarily stimulated by calcium influx when a post-synaptic cell is stimulated</li>
            <li>they travel retrograde and attach to CB1 and CB2 receptors on pre-synaptic cells, which decreases calcium influx, thereby modulating release of excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmitters from the presynaptic cells.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>In immune/inflammatory response, they modulate T- and B-lymphocyte proliferation, migration, apoptosis, and cytokine production.</li>
        <li>In muscle cells they reduce energy expenditure</li>
        <li>In liver and adipose cells they increase glucose uptake and lipogenesis, decrease insulin sensitivity, and decrease lipolysis, resulting in energy storage.</li>
        <li>In addition to activating CB1 and CB2 receptors, endocannabinoids interact with other receptors:
          <ul>
            <li>TRPV1 (Transient Receptor Potential Vanilloid Type- 1) activation-modulates pain and inflammation</li>
            <li>PPARG (Peroxisome Proliferator Activated Receptor gamma) activation-resulting in neuroprotection, improved memory and cognition, analgesia, and anti-tumor effects</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class='fd-references print-hidden'>
        <p><strong>External References</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href='https://www.nature.com/articles/s41380-018-0215-1'>Endocannabinoid Effect on Psychological Stress</a>, <em>Nature Journal</em> online</li>
          <li><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6444701/'>Endocannabinoid Effect on Energy Expenditure</a>, <em>NCBI</em></li>
