  <section class='fd-faq' id='f3'>
    <p class='fd-faqheader'>How does Cannabidiol (CBD) interact with the Endocannabinoid System and other receptors?</p>
    <div class='fd-answer'>
      <ul>
        <li>CBD is a non-psychoactive Phytocannabinoid that interacts with the Endocannabinoid System, some enzymes, and ion channels
          <div class='center-quote'>NOTE:  WHETHER THESE INTERACTIONS RESULT IN CLINICALLY SIGNIFICANT EFFECTS HAS ONLY BEEN DEMONSTRATED IN HIGH QUALITY CLINICAL TRIALS OF ITS USE IN TREATING SOME SEIZURE DISORDERS</div>
        </li>
        <li>CBD is not a ligand for CB1 or CB2 receptors: Its a negative allosteric modulator, binding to the CB1 and CB2 receptors and changing the 3 dimensional shape of their receptor site, modulating the effect of ligands.</li>
        <li>It is an antagonist of GPR55 (G Protein-coupled Receptor 55, felt to possibly be an endocannabinoid receptor).  GPR55 inactivation inhibits some cancer cells that over express GPR55 (common in colorectal, pancreatic, and colon cancer).</li>
        <li>It binds with receptors which are not part of the endocannabinoid system
          <ul>
            <li>It selectively inhibits COX-2.  COX-2 inhibition results in pain modulation; has an anti-inflammatory effect and anti-tumor effects</li>
            <li>It activates PPARgamma.  Activation is neuroprotective; improves memory and cognition; has analgesic and anti-tumor effects.</li>
            <li>It activates TRPV1.  Activation modulates pain and inflammation.</li>
            <li>It activates the serotonin receptor 5-HT1A (5-Hydroxytryptamine Receptor Subtype 1A).  Activation of 5-HT1A results in an anti-inflammatory, anti-anxiety, anti-depressant effect.</li>
            <li>It activates the Adenosine A2A receptor, and inhibits Adenosine uptake via Phospholipase-A2.  Activation of A2A and reuptake inhibition has an anti-inflammatory, neuroprotective, effect.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>It deactivates FAAH (Fatty Acid Amide Hydrolase), the enzyme which metabolizes Anandamide and 2-AG, enhancing their effects.  FAAH deactivation results in higher levels of Anandamide in the brain, which has a calming effect, blunting the persistence of the fight-flight response (part of the mechanism for developing PTSD).</li>
        <li>It has an inhibitory effect on some Na+ and Ca++ ion channels, thus slowing neuron firing.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class='fd-references print-hidden'>
