  <section class='fd-faq' id='f11'>
    <p class='fd-faqheader'>How is CBD metabolized?</p>
    <div class='fd-answer'>
      <ul>
        <li>Major route of metabolism is the liver
          <ul>
            <li>Primarily by Cytochrome P450 (CYP2C group and CYP3A group). Of note, coumadin is metabolized by a CYP2C enzyme.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>CBD undergoes significant first pass metabolism in the liver.
          <ul>
            <li>90% of orally ingested CBD undergoes first pass metabolism in the liver</li>
            <li>Because of first pass metabolism, Sublingual/buccal mucosa administration is the preferred route of administration if systemic effects are desired, or topically if local effects are.</li>
            <li>It can also be smoked and absorbed in the lungs, but long term harmful effects of this route of administration are not known.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class='fd-references print-hidden'>
        <p><strong>External References</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href='https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/product/602/smpc#gref'>Pharmacokinetics/interactions/ dosing/precautions</a>, <em>Medicines.org</em></li>
          <li><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2689518/'>CBD Metabolism - First Pass effect</a>, <em>NCBI</em></li>
